-- India's Sensitive Index Declines as Investors Flee Risk; Bharti Slides
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-11-23T11:02:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-23/jaiprakash-icici-bank-lead-sensex-index-decline-on-global-economy-outlook.html
India’s benchmark stock index
slid as an artillery exchange between North and South Korea
prompted investors to flee riskier assets amid investor concern
global economic growth may falter.  Bharti Airtel Ltd. , the nation’s largest mobile-phone
operator, dropped for the first time in six days. The
confrontation between the countries added to losses on Asian
markets after Moody’s Investors Service warned it may downgrade
Ireland.  State Bank of India , the biggest lender, retreated to
its lowest level since Sept. 8.  “It’s the Korean effect,” said  Ambareesh Baliga , vice-
president at Karvy Stock Broking Ltd. “There is a certain
amount of nervousness in the markets.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s  Sensitive Index , or  Sensex ,
lost 265.75, or 1.3 percent, to 19,691.84, as of the 3:30 p.m.
close in Mumbai, after earlier sliding as much as 3.1 percent,
the most in a year. The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National
Stock Exchange dropped 1.3 percent to 5,934.75. The  BSE 200
Index  retreated 1.2 percent to 2,497.36.  Bharti slid 2.3 percent to 329.15 rupees.  Reliance
Industries Ltd. , the most valuable company, lost 1.6 percent to
995.6 rupees, its lowest level since Sept. 30.  Jaiprakash
Associates Ltd. , a builder of dams, roads and bridges, retreated
1.7 percent to 123.65 rupees.  DLF Ltd. , the biggest developer,
decreased 1 percent to 315.6 rupees.  Regional Losses  The  MSCI Asia Pacific excluding Japan Index  fell the most
since June after Yonhap News reported the exchanges between
South Korea and nuclear-armed North Korea. Moody’s Investors
Service said Ireland’s bailout may increase the nation’s debt
burden and pose a “credit negative” for the country.  “Over the next one or two months we will see such
corrections due to the global concerns, even as the long-term
growth in India looks good,” said  Apurva Shah , head of research
at Prabhudas Lilladher Pvt. in Mumbai.  State Bank plunged 2.8 percent to 2,953.4 rupees.  ICICI
Bank Ltd. , the second-biggest lender, declined 2 percent to
1,156.95 rupees.  Stocks on the Sensex are valued at 18.6 times estimated
earnings after the gauge jumped 13 percent this year, the best
performance and most expensive among the world’s 10 biggest
stock markets, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Foreign fund inflows have almost doubled this year to an
all-time high on the expectation consumer spending will boost
corporate earnings.  Overseas  investors  bought a net  14.43 billion rupees 
($318.9 million) of Indian shares on Nov. 19, taking this year’s
record flows to 1.31 trillion rupees, according to data on the
 website  of the Securities and Exchange Board of India.  To contact the reporter on this story:
